Comments to editor:

------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Comments to author(s):

The  paper  describes a   maximal  tractable   class of   soft  binary
constraints:  the  ones for which the  evaluation  of each constraints
corresponds to a  binary   submodular function.   In this  case,   the
evaluations   functions can  be   expressed as  a   sum of generalized
interval functions and the problem can be solved as a minimum weighted
cut on a directed  graph.  Proofs of  tractability and of the fact the
language  is   maximally tractable  are provided.    The class of soft
binary constraints is illustrated with several examples.

I  have few  comments  about  the heart   of the paper,  that is   the
definition of the class of soft constraints that is considered and the
proof  that it  is    maximally  tractable. Everything is    carefully
explained, it is well written and organized. The proofs are not always
easy to follow but the figures really help. So my main comment is that
it is a very good paper that represents a significant amount of work.

One   thing which is hard to    figure out is  how   big is the set of
submodular binary constraints.  In  the paper, there are many examples
of  submodular   binary  constraints   and    only  one  example    of
non-submodular one  (but a very  important one  in practice):  x!=y. I
think it  would  be  interesting  to give   a  few  other examples  of
non-submodular binary constraints.

In the conclusion: the last sentence reads  "By combining these ideas,
we  obtain a flexible and powerful   modeling language with a provably
efficient solution strategy".   This affirmation seems  a bit too much
categorical. It is not clear that the results in the paper can lead to
some "efficient" solution strategy as the complexity in O(n^3|D|^3) is
not really realistic for a  practical implementation unless for  small
problems and small domains of variables.  Of course, the piece of work
described in  the article is an important  step in this  direction but
I'm not convinced that  the proposed algorithms are,  as such, of very
practical interest. So I think this last sentence should be soften.

It would be interesting to see if part of the results presented in the
article using the concept of submodular function  could be extended to
n-ary   soft constraints. For  instance,  is  the  space of submodular
ternary constraints polynomial or not ?

A couple of minor comments or typos

* Close to  the top of page  10, after the decomposition of "\Psi(x)",
  one should   add   something  like   "so  each unary  function    is
  submodular."

* On the first list item on page 4, the font used  for "min" and "max"
  is not the same as the  one for "max" and "plus"  whereas I think it
  should be

